T1  - Cross-Cutting Ties, Organizational Density, and New Firm Formation in the U.S. Biotech Industry, 1994–98
AU  - Bae, Jonghoon
AU  - Wezel, Filippo Carlo
AU  - Koo, Jun
Y1  - 2011/04/01
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.60263089
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2011.60263089
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 295
EP  - 311
VL  - 54
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study examines the role of cooperative relations among incumbents in the formation of new firms. We argue that cooperative interfirm relations that bridge geographically remote and diverse sources of knowledge?cross-cutting ties?contribute to new firm formation. Employing data on state-level entries into the U.S. biotech industry from 1994 to 1998, we find support for the following hypotheses: the formation of new firms in a focal region of an industry is positively related to the number of cross-cutting ties; the number of cross-cutting ties negatively moderates the effects of organizational density on the formation of new firms.
AB  - This study examines the role of cooperative relations among incumbents in the formation of new firms. We argue that cooperative interfirm relations that bridge geographically remote and diverse sources of knowledge?cross-cutting ties?contribute to new firm formation. Employing data on state-level entries into the U.S. biotech industry from 1994 to 1998, we find support for the following hypotheses: the formation of new firms in a focal region of an industry is positively related to the number of cross-cutting ties; the number of cross-cutting ties negatively moderates the effects of organizational density on the formation of new firms.
